\ Logic-var declaration.  `lvar to x` makes a persistent global logic var
\ (`to` auto-creates the global); `| ?x |` is a fresh-per-call local logic
\ var.  Capitalization is stylistic convention only.  ~ is unify, ? is deref.

\ === a declared global is the same var at every mention ===
lvar to Same
Same Same = . cr                           \ 1   same name, same var
lvar to One   lvar to Two
One Two = . cr                             \ 0   distinct vars
lvar to Unbound
Unbound ? Unbound = . cr                   \ 1   deref of an unbound var is itself

\ === binding a global var ===
lvar to Bound
Bound 5 ~ drop   Bound ? 5 = . cr          \ 1

\ === a global var persists its binding across lines (unlike Prolog) ===
lvar to Persist
Persist 11 ~ drop
Persist ? 11 = . cr                        \ 1

\ === aliasing two globals: binding one binds the other ===
lvar to Al1   lvar to Al2
Al1 Al2 ~ drop   Al1 7 ~ drop   Al2 ? 7 = . cr   \ 1

\ === vars inside structures bind via unify ===
lvar to AP   lvar to BP
[ AP BP ] [ 1 2 ] ~ drop   AP ? 1 = .  BP ? 2 = . cr   \ 1 1
lvar to Fk
{ :k Fk } { :k "v" :x 9 } ~ drop   Fk ? "v" = . cr     \ 1

\ === | ?x | is a fresh local logic var, bound per call ===
: bindit  | ?X >n |  X n ~ drop  X ? ;
3 bindit . cr                              \ 3
7 bindit . cr                              \ 7   fresh X each call; no clash with 3

: twovars  | ?A ?B |  [ A B ] [ 8 9 ] ~ drop  A ? . B ? . cr ;
twovars                                    \ 8 9

\ === a receive local keeps its received value (not a fresh lvar) ===
: idr  | >R |  R ;
42 idr . cr                                \ 42

\ === ? locals work inside a quotation ===
[: | ?Q |  Q 5 ~ drop  Q ? :] execute . cr  \ 5

\ === an undeclared capitalized token is just an unknown word ===
Stray

bye
